Accentuated eccentric loading (AEL) is an awesome tool you can use as an athlete to elicit very fast adaptations towards explosive power. The idea is to have a very controlled eccentric(down) portion, where you can either count the descent or simply go slow at your own pervcieved rate (we have had success with structured and unstructured drop counts), and then as fast as possible transition to the concentric (up) phase of the lift with as much force and intent as possible. As you transition to the concentric phase of the lift. Your spotter should actively assist your ascent to accelerate the process. This is a key component of the process. 

You don’t need high tech equipment for this, a squat bar and a partner is sufficient enough.

Become more explosive immediately with these 3 movements 🔥🚨💪🏼

This contrast is designed to train an athlete to absorb and redirect force thru the posterior chain and is a great first phase before moving on to more complex systems. 

It begins with a strength primer of the posterior chain, the Nordic Curl. In this case, we are using a slow eccentric variation, but it can also be done with fast eccentrics, isometric efforts, and other versions. We went with slow to work on tissue resiliency, and because we are in an eccentric phase of training with the Combine group. 

The next movement we used was the hang power snatch since this was the big power lift of the series. Here is where we train the body to produce force explosively. We want lots of power generated here. Most of it once again coming from the posterior chain. HP snatch is one of our most utilized barbell movements to express explosive power and promote full lower half joint extension. 

The final movement of the series is the eccentric depth drop. Since our goal was to cue the body on how to best absorb forces, we added more acceleration and force to the movement by dropping of the box with weight, while being pushed down into the ground. This greatly increases ground reactive forces on landings and forces serious eccentric and isometric power to control the landing. Athletes are cued to land stiff with minimal joint bend, and really try to “smash the brakes” as they hit the ground. Strong ability to absorb forces eccentrically has been identified as a key marker in max speed and agility ability, even more so than concentric strength. It gives you stiffer and springer responses from ground contact.

What lift is a must have in your training program? 🤔🧐💪🏼💯

Heres mine! This post shouldn’t have any controversy but undoubtedly will. I’m gonna start by saying, if I had to pick one piece of equipment I could not do without I’m the gym, it would be the trap bar (hex bar).
But why?
Well, it’s as simple as this. The trap bar deadlift is the one movement no athlete should do without. It allows you to pull enormous amounts of weight at angles that are closer to athletic movements than traditional deadlifts. (And this is coming from one of the few performance coaches that actually loves the traditional deadlift). But there is no denying that the handles being at the side makes it easier to get into a strong pull posture and, as I mentioned, more natural to sporting movements. It’s also a combination of pulling and pushing. It’s a cross of a squat and deadlift in a way for most athletes. It allows athletes to find their most comfortable position to drive weight. Critical to letting them find what works best for them..high hip hinge, big knee bend, more neutral position. It is all possible and will give each athlete a chance to further develop natural strengths while improving weaknesses. It’s also the best way to get longer limb athletes to safely execute max strength efforts.
.

Need Bounce?? 🐰💪
.
High hurdle reactive hops, jumps, or bounds are still one of the most useful exercises to create explosiveness and spring in the legs. It amazes me how under utilized it is in the performance community. This should be done in pretty much any athletic program to some extent, and honestly if I saw someone program it year round, I’d applaud them.
.

Using a reactive force off the ground to help the recovery phase, and knee tuck is reflective of so many athletic movements, not to mention the timing and coordination factors involved. Limiting ground contact times while maintaining vertical heights and air control promotes more force development and spring in the legs. Whether it is vertical leap improvement, speed increases, or all around athleticism you are after, high hurdle jumps should absolutely be present at some point in your programming.
.

Over the last couple years you may have heard some performance or speed guys, even researchers argue how the transfer to running isn’t there because running takes up way less ground contact times than these sort of plyometrics. If the case against using drills other than running to promote speed has any validity, then all you should be doing is running. Stop jumping, squatting, deadlifting, plyometrics, and stability drills altogether. What we are after are not direct effects for running, but physicall markers that will aid in the biomechanical demands of running. In this case, rigidity and spring, coordination and movement timing, and force production even if it is at slower rates. All these are indicators of fast and explosive runners. And all these indicators can be improved by this great old school drill.
.

Certain Injuries shouldn’t stop you from training‼️

When athletes are going through injuries, it’s important to have actionable plans ready to keep them progressing. Coaches often call this Plan B and sometimes even need a plan C. The benefits are various.

1. The athlete can find ways to keep progression even in limited amounts by doing movements close to what the Plan A actions were, and some progress will a better than getting worse by sitting idle.

2. It keeps the athlete in some type of form so that the transition back to full action is more seemless. Having a baseline is key to getting back in top form faster.

3. Athletes who go idle due to an injury often experience the same injury all over again by rushing right back to where they were without improvement first. They try to get back to the shape where they suffered the injury, and never get to address the issues that caused it to begin with.
Plan B and C training is a great time to address the underlying issues and fix them by the time is back to speed.
.
.

These will increase your lateral explosiveness 💨⚡️
.
1. Lateral Skater Bounds
-the focus is on allowing the torso to rotate and involving the spinal/pelvic engine as the outside leg does the absorbing and pushing. 
-Outside leg change of direction is the most common lateral movement in most sports, learning to absorb lateral forces and redirecting them is key.
-Here the foot, ankle, quads, and glutes must work in harmony to produce the right amount of tension at the right time to get in and out of braking.
-Adding the medball forces more spinal/pelvic engine involvement that works in aiding deceleration and acceleration in the movement.

2. Lateral Plyo Box Hops
-These provide much more ground forces for the athlete to have to recover from than ground based plyos, adding to more tissue development and motor unit coordination.
-Giving an athlete a landing mark further from the box will create even more needs to redirect force explosively and at more lateral angles. 
-Adding a single leg touch down back to the box helps cue some of the stability factors associated with COD.
.
From a performance standpoint, lateral movement and change of direction (COD) training should focus on the tissue’s (muscle, tendon, fascia) ability to absorb force rabidly and redirect forces with maximal power. The tissue must be strong and stable enough to stop directional forces without energy leaks, and still have enough reactive force production to produce power in the change of direction. This is a careful combination of building tendon stiffness, muscle activation, and fascial springiness.The next component is to create a coordination pattern that maximizes movement angles to push with efficiency and effectiveness in a given direction. This comes from breaking down movement within each athletes own bandwidth of strength capacity and movement control. By giving them a rudimentary basis to begin to explore more effective angles, they can begin to develop their own movement capabilities.
.
.

Dancing Makes You Faster! READ BELOW! ⚡️🔥💨

Dancing has two components that are fully relatable to sprint effectiveness. Rhythm and pushing the ground. As far as push goes, try any dance move, running man, salsa, moonwalk, line dancing, breakdancing, ballet, etc. Try to do that move without pushing the ground, you can’t. 

For the rhythm. Dancing obviously follows a cadence based on the beat. Fluidity in sprinting comes from finding a specific cadence as well. The rhythm of that cadence should sound like faster and faster ground taps. It should feel like it too, a speed up in the beat. 

@coach_vince_anderson  says “there is no drive phase, it’s all drive phase. The entire race is your drive phase.” 
To a certain degree this makes sense. If you are pushing as hard as you can with the intention of bringng yourself to a tall upright max speed position, and when in that position your goal is to keep pushing for more speed, as it should be, then technically there is some truth to that statement. At least from an attacking mentality, that is spot on. 

Now, if you forget everything else, when it comes to your sprinting, remember you have got to push as violently as you can, while building your cadence. 
.
.

Are you looking to take your sprinting to the next level?
Heavy sled sprints might be the best option yet  by building functional, movement specific strength and power in your lower body, they can drastically improve your acceleration and even top-end speed. The key aspects that heavy sleds promote include the following.
1. Foot/ankle stiffness, by having to push the ground at high rates of force with heavier loads the ankle musculature automatically goes into locked in mode, which helps develop stiff and receive muscles of the lower leg and feet, that will convert more effective power when sprinting. 
2. It cues better angles of projection, the heavier loads provide instant feedback to the athlete about how to best push yo get the most efficiency without having to overdue acceleration mechanics
3. It also cues better hip extension to get the most off every foot impact.
4. Teaches athletes to attack their acceleration with violence and aggression.

5. Another great benefit is that it gets athletes to stop spinning their wheels and promotes better recovery movement patterns that generate more efficiency and effectiveness in acceleration their mechanics. 

Plus, they’re a low-impact exercise that reduces the risk of injury.

These 5 Pillars Will Guarantee Your Athletic Success 💯💪
.
1️⃣Mobility/stability
•Joint flexibility is important to be able to get into random positions that sport will require.
•Stability within the joints will make sure that the flexible angles are protected against injury.
•End ranges of motion require more strength than most athletes have, the stronger the end range, the more control of that end range, the safer the athlete will be.

2️⃣Strength 
•Strength dictates movement.
•Strength is still in the equation of every force and power equation.
•Without strength there is no force, without force, there is no power, without power you won’t be explosive.
•If you are not a freak athletic outlier, strength is the first tool in the tool box that will make you a better athlete instantly.
•Strength is a component of mobility and stability, and adds to both mobility and stability.

3️⃣Explosive power & speed
•Speed is the number one predictor of athletic success.
•Speed of movement is what turns strength to power. Power is the second predictor of athletic success. 
•The more power you can apply the faster you will be.
•Begin to see how all these things intertwine and integrate together. This is what makes these pillars the perfect benchmark for athleticism.

4️⃣Coordination/movement skills
•Coordination of movement is what makes your speed and your force production relevant to the movement requirements of your sport.
•Movement skills, understanding and executing movement at optimal angles, will dictate how well you change direction, jump, land, accelerate, throw, and even catch.

5️⃣Sports endurance 
•Endurance is the ability to repeat the movement requirements of that sport over and over again with optimal intensity, force production, speed, and efficiency.
•Power repeatability will help keep you explosive into the late stages of a game. 
•Working the right metabolic demands of your sport will ensure you have energy to last you an entire game, and that you can call on reserves when needed.

Get more Explosive! 🧨💪
.
Transfer of power from eccentric to concentric is what makes an athlete explosive. There is always a curve of eccentric load before a concentric reaction, often known as the stretch shortening cycle, made popular by plyometric movements. The fact is that the stretch shortening cycle exists in nearly 100% of sporting movements to one degree or another. The faster and the stronger you can preload eccentrically, the more explosively you will redirect those forces concentrically.

Priming the body with a heavy and dynamic eccentric into an iso hold like the trap bar deadlift, then transitioning to an aggressive drop jump at max heights will illicit the demands listed above, gearing you towards more explosive athletic potential on the field or court. It is taking the components of the stretch shortening cycle and compounding their effects bith at the tissue and neural levels.

Are These Better Than Squats!? 🤷‍♂️🤔💪
.
Step back lunges may be superior to squats for athetic strength.

Most sports movements are either done on one leg or with one leg delivering most of the ground forces. This makes the step back lunges a more transferable exercise towards sporting needs. Because it does provide single leg focus in a bilateral movement, there is a great amount of coordination happening between both limbs, which also leads to more hip control adaptations. Stability is also a great benefit of the step back lunge finding balance as the rear leg leaves the ground then catches again while bending at the lower leg joints makes an athlete really focus on their balance. Step back lunges also do a great job of activating the posterior chain. They tend to be less stressful on the knees than other lunge and squat variations, which is great for athletes who suffer from various knee issues. 

Going heavy with a loaded barbell accentuates all these adaptations to another level, and thus we recommend that athletes go as heavy as they can for a rep range. You will notice the heavier you go the harder it is to maintain posture and stability and to execute a great lunge. This is the stress we want to add. If the barbell is too difficult to control for an athlete, we recommend scaling it to DBs, but still try to go heavy.
.

Try these to level up your rotational strength and stability! ⚾️💪💣

In this video, you’ll see two variations of the drill. The first involves landing on a bosu ball before delivering the medball toss, which forces the athlete to use their hips to absorb and deliver rotational forces. The second variation involves delivering the toss on solid ground, making it much closer to the real thing and using more ground forces to deliver rotational force.

By eccentrically pre-loading the system in multiple ways, this drill adds tons of effect to a traditional scoop toss. The dynamic eccentric factors overload stability and rotational bias, making this a superior option for learning how to load and deliver torque.

Strengthen Your Ankles! 🦶🦵💪

The nearest joints to the ground reside in the foot and ankle. Yet, this is often one of the least trained areas in sport performance. Training the tissue of the foot and ankle to be resilient, strong, and mobile is a great way to quickly improve athletic ability and limit limb injuries. You need to build tissue tolerance to stress in many areas of the ankle, starting with the Achilles tendon, but also the tibialis posterior, anterior tibialis, and peroneus. This is not including the many tendons within the foot. 

We tackle the demands of the foot/ankle by directly training the tissue of the area and then working the coordination and motor recruitment requirements of movement along various directions. 

The first training tool is specific isometric exercises to target tissues of the Achilles tendon and foot. Our Achilles prep series is a great way to train the Achilles tendon prior to high output sport and training regimens, such as sprinting, jumping, cutting, and feels that require a lot of starting and stopping. 

From there, we will go into movements that begin to build rigidity at the foot ankle as the rest of the limb moves dynamically. Rigidity of the foot ankle as force is applied thru the ground is one of the most important keys to athletic prowess. 

Next, we work on the proprioceptive nature of lateral and medial stability along with lateral and medial force absorption ability of the foot/ankle. This can be done with slow deliberate sideways jumping and landing, as well as with quicker more ballistic “pogo-like” variations of single log hops. 

The final stage is actual sprint, plyometric, and sport actions.

•Accentuated Eccentric Loading (AEL) is a training technique that emphasizes making the “down” phase of a lift (the eccentric phase) harder than the “up” phase (the concentric phase). This approach has gained attention in the sports performance community.

•Eccentric loading, or the phase when muscles lengthen while under tension, is vital for effective movement patterns in sports. If an athlete can’t generate force during the eccentric phase, they’ll struggle to use that force during the concentric phase, such as jumping or changing direction rapidly.

•AEL training focuses on two key aspects. First, it involves lifting heavy weights during the eccentric phase to challenge the muscles and tendons. Then, it requires the athlete to rapidly lift lighter weights during the concentric phase. This teaches the body to transition quickly and forcefully from eccentric to concentric actions, similar to what athletes do when cutting or jumping.

•Traditionally, AEL training has been done using specialized tools like weight release hooks or mechanical instruments with cables to adjust loads. However, these tools can be costly and time-consuming to set up.

•An alternative approach, which doesn’t add costs, involves coaches. They can increase resistance during the eccentric phase by pushing down on the barbell or resistance being used. Alternatively, they can assist the athlete during the concentric phase, helping them activate muscles more rapidly. These variations can be used interchangeably, with the assisted concentric version being somewhat safer.

•Typically, AEL training is programmed for about 3 to 4 weeks because it can be demanding on the nervous system. Moreover, AEL can serve as a valuable foundation for advanced exercises like accelerated eccentric plyometrics, where athletes experience more resistance during the eccentric portion and then an instant reduction in resistance during the concentric phase, akin to giving AEL a turbo boost.

Add strength bands to your lifts!

Using strength bands when you squat impacts a couple of very important adaptations to force production.

The main thing that accommodated (band resistance added) squats will do is force you to keep generating higher levels of force through the full range of motion. This will lead to greater force production through the top range of the squat, and more closely represents what happens when we perform an athletic feat such as accelerating or jumping. When you perform a regular squat, you actually push much less, and use less muscle activation as you get closer to the standing position, but when you accelerate or jump you are pushing through a full range of motion with maximal force production for the entirety of the “push”. Adding bands forces the athlete to mimic this action because as the athlete stands out of the bottom of the squat the load continues to increase. Depending on the banded load, if an athlete is not actively pushing to accelerate through the range of motion, they will not come up efficiently. Likewise, if an athlete is not trying to accelerate through their projection during acceleration, they will not be effective in building speed. Same principle applies to jumping, the more you can accelerate through the jumping motion, especially towards the end range of extension, the higher you will project into the air. 

Another benefit of accommodated resistance that is related to the same mechanical concepts is the activation of muscles through the concentric phase. Again, the fact that the bands add ever increasing resistance through the concentric range of motion allows us to build more strength and get more muscle activation out of parts of the movement range that typically get very little returns. This helps drive purposeful force production and muscle strength.

🚨Heres Why! 📝

• Promotes great mobility.

•Emphasizes strength and stability through a large range of rotation.

•On the eccentric portion you are first releasing the shoulder, then the scapula then rotating along the T-spine, finishing in a big stretch throughout the upper posterior chain, all the while fighting the tension of the band.
•During the concentric portion you are reversing the action trying to get good scapula contraction using muscles that include the lower trapezius among other shoulder and scapula stabilizers and continuing to rotate concetrically at the T-spine, getting even more activation until end range.

•This also happens to follow the opposite action of an arm swing during a throw in a slow and controlled movement, working the antagonist muscles of the throwing action, which is important for overall stability and health.

Some times some training may cause times to get slower and then get faster then back slower again and back and forth in waves. So long as the long term curve is trading up we are in a good training regimen. Learning to read the waves and even predict them will help training efforts over the long haul.

🚨An emphasis on reason number 3. If nothing else, intent is key. And intent is always best driven with a strong stimulus. There is no better stimulus than having immediate feedback on your performance and effort. Timing sprints makes guys work harder on each rep. If nothing else, this is worth all the reasons to consistently time sprints. 

We time 30s, splits within those 30s, 40s, 60s, 120s even 200s. We do splits within those, as those paint a clearer picture of what’s going on thru the sprint. We also do flys like 10 or 20 meter flys. We measure distances in both yards and meters.

Try these if you wanna be a stronger athlete 💪🏼⚡️

First and foremost, understand that this is a leg exercise, not a shoulder or arm drill. 

1. Rely on a strong hip hinge with minimal knee bend to target the hips, glutes, and hamstrings. 
2. Try to swing the KB down as fast as possible and wait until the last possible second to hinge at the hips. 
3. Once you begin to swing back forward use a fast action of hip and knee extension, be powerful and forceful, and try to get the KB to swing as high as even chest level by only using the momentum of the hip action. 
4. Keep strong control of the shoulder by keeping scapula and lat muscles engaged thru the motion.
5. Keep the body from rotating and hips shifting because of the uneven weight. 

This drill is a great way to get the same benefits to the posterior chain and fast hip activation action of a conventional KB swing but ads a new level of antir rotational and hip control work, as the body must compensate for the offset weight to one side of the body. Similarly you will get much greater shoulder dynamic stability because of this same single arm action to adjust for.

Here’s how to become a better athlete with less injuries! 🤕

 That’s not going to happen by standing on a stability ball. You need real strength output while finding that coordination and balance. These over and back lunges are a perfect tool for that. 

As you try to do these lunges heavier and heavier you will notice that you not only need more hip, leg, and core strength to get in and out of each position, but that the balance and stability requirements get more and more exhausting the heavier you go.

This exercise is awesome for all athletes of any sport as the carry over is about hip strength and total body control. When athletes get really good at this they can go as heavy as 275 with the bar and do 5 plus reps in each direction.

Start light with these, or even with no weight, and gradually build up as you begin to find your balance and control.

This is also a great rehab drill if you are coming off an injury.

Heres a secret weapon we use to build functional strength and power, that translates to athletic success. 

A few years back, we started adding a floating heel variation. What does adding a floating heel do? 

1. It gives us a hefty isometric load at the foot and ankle, especially at heavier weights, and this is the foot/ankle strength we are after when being explosive athletes. Ismoetric strength and stiffness thru force development is what we want at the foot/ankle.

2. With the heel floating and limited foot contacts to the ground, force the ball of the foot and the big toe to push maximally, which leads to better glute engagement.

3. Because of the single leg variation and the limited foot contact on the ground to just the front of the foot, it creates more stability as well. 

4. Single leg DL is one of the very best ways to train the posterior chain (glutes, hamstrings, and calf muscles) with a movement pattern that closely resembles athletic postures. 

5. Also, the single leg variation really focuses on single leg strength and takes away bilateral biases. 

Make sure you keep the foot parallel to the ground and don’t let the heel drop or raise much as you lift up. As you pull the weight begin with your posterior chain activated. You should feel significant tension on your hamstring and glutes before you even begin to pull. Upper body wise, keep your lats engaged, core engaged, and lower back stiff. 

This is an awesome exercise for sprinters, baseball players, jumpers, throwers, etc.

Did you know lateral movements can improve linear speed?? 🔥💪🏼
.
Why would a straight line sprinter need lateral hops? 

1. As you better control explosive lateral movements you are getting great eccentric return of lateral control, many sprinters as the accelerate lose a lot of energy laterally and aren’t able to focus all of their force production in a linear effort.

2. Continuous lateral jumps also
Require dynamic core control, which is essential for sprinters.

3. When the height of the barrier or the lateral distance of the barrier is pushed to the athletes limits, it becomes an incredibly intense plyometric exercise that requires a lot of foot and ankle stiffness and stability, along with a ton of knee and hip spring. These are the literal requirements of elite sprinting. Not to mention the control factor. 

4. They are a great plyometric movement for athletes that can not sprint because of a hamstring injury. You can still get great explosiveness without taxing the hamstrings too bad when you go with a shorter and narrow barrier and still get all the springy action you want at the ankles and knees.

5. Just like we say that speed can help agility. The reverse is also true. The athletes that can be more agile and can be more explosive laterally will typically be able to be better sprinters. 

6. Depending on the reps, you can use these jumps to improve power endurance or power repeatability. Doing 20 continuous reps at a challenging height or length will really stretch your metabolic demands. Do 5 to 6 sets, and you are really in for a taxing training session.
